<br>
As for rube goldberg contraptions, have you ever looked at the rube goldberg process that made the CPU chip you are using to read this?  We have a GOOD grip on handling complexity.  (Of course, I would happily pull a page from the poor X-33 program to lower the complexity of this booster as much as possible.  Note the lack of things like landing gear or a hydraulic system.)<br>
<br>
Now, you said :<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  And don't bother coming up with a tightly engineered rube-goldberg mitigation procedure for this problem.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Okay, I'll solve the risk issues of a total loss in boost phase without touching the engineering  of the craft at all, I promise.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  It is only the risks involved in using such a craft at sub-orbital speeds that concerns me. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ahhh, okay, now we are making progress again.  Here is a clear statement of your position, and it makes excellent sense.  Let me see what I can do.<br>
<br>
I will concur, the boost phase is far and away the most dangerous time, although the powered descent is pretty close.  Yet I am completely comfortable that we can launch this booster with readily acceptable risk levels.<br>
<br>
How, you ask? <br>
<br>
If you will recall, I stated the risk of this design could be easily mitigated through careful design <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  and the proper launch site. </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I have already detailed a good chunk of the booster to you.  ( There is MUCH more, though.  Ask about crew shielding, life support, power generation, and OMS/RCS thrusters.)<br>
<br>
But the launch site is just as critical to risk mitigation as the booster design is.<br>
<br>
<br>
So, let me introduce you to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.bartleby.com/151/c21.html"> Baker Island </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> one of those little islands in the Pacific that the US happens to own.  Baker Island is SMACK on the equator, completely uninhabited, and best of all, has a 12 nautical mile territorial waters zone which is US property.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
So, we sail a moderate sized container ship to the territorial waters which has our spaceship on board.  This ship is also the launch platform.  Yes, I am advocating launching the booster from a ship at sea.  Yes, I know this will present difficulties.  If they are too difficult to overcome, we will simply launch from Baker Island.  Its not like there's anything there to hurt....  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Now, looking east from Bakers Island, the next piece of significant land is the Galapagos Islands, a whopping 9,400 kilometers to the east.  <br>
<br>
9400 kilometers!!!<br>
<br>
The circumference of LEO at an altitude of 222 kilometers is 41,470 kilometers.  <br>
<br>
Now, lets assume the engines on the booster burn for ten minutes to get us up to launch speed, and an orbit lasts 90 minutes at that altitude.  So, being VERY conservative we say the boost phase lasts for one ninth of an orbit, or 4607 kilometers.  (In actuality, I estimate the boost phase would end at 3500 kilometers, but the math to know for sure is pretty savage.)<br>
<br>
So, the boost phase begins at incredibly remote Baker Island, and ends 4800 kilometers BEFORE you reach the deserted Galapagos Islands.  Boost phase ends over 6000 kilometers before you cross South America.<br>
<br>
If we assume the worst case scenario you are so fond of, the booster gets pulverized into rubble just before the end of boost phase.  There is a total release of the fuel mass, which is a gas.   This gas will decelerate VERY quickly, no matter how attenuated the atmosphere is.  I cannot see any way the 60 reactor masses worth of  release materials can go anywhere except into the Pacific.   Which has successfully been used to mitigate FAR worse releases than even this worse case scenario multiple times, including several all stacked up on top of each other timewise.<br>
<br>
If there is a lesser disaster during boost, the reactors scram into the fuel storage systems and those systems sink into the deep ocean.  We can safely ignore them, or go get them at our leisure.  If they fail and release their radioactive cargo, it still gets absorbed into the Pacific and diluted into harmlessness.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  A disintegrating high pressure LH2 turbopump can (and has) tear apart the booster.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You are correct, which is why the pumps I am using are the most sturdy, most developed, and most reliable pumps in history, and THEN I run them at only 88 percent of capacity, even though they can reach 109 percent capacity safely.  Remember, this is a relaxed design.  Well inside the performance envelope in all cases.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  There is trivial risk in transporting fresh uranium fuel into high orbit.   <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree!  Oh, PLEASE ask me about the fuel cycle, pretty please?  I already asked once!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Heck, once you hear about that part of the plan you may just start saying this is the best thing since sliced bread.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  A gas-core nuclear rocket assembled and fueled there could travel to Mars in a matter of weeks.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
&lt;sigh&gt;  I completely concur with you, and BOY am I eager to start.   But you accuse ME of wishful thinking, then you start expecting chemical fuels to get us into space in any significant way.  <br>
<br>
HOW are we going to get our gas cored rocket into orbit in the first place?  Go back to building Saturn V's?  Try to build Sea Dragons?  Remember, for doing things like capturing asteroids, SIZE COUNTS.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
The most energetic conventional fuel mixture I am aware of is Liquid Oxygen as the oxidiser and a mix of 53 percent Beryllium and 47 percent Hydrogen as fuel, with a calculated vacuum Isp of 522.  This is about fifteen percent better than oxygen and hydrogen,  and  is poisonous to boot.  Compare this to the Isp of 3060 I posit for my design. There is no comparison.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Exotic metastable propellants could do better.  Monatomic hydrogen has a theoretical Isp of 2100 or so, and spin stabilised triple helium has a theoretical Isp of 3000 or better.  The only problem is that these are completely hypothetical at the moment.  Plus, the helium engine has reaction temperatures up in the 16,000 kelvin range!  Heck, the lighbulb would be EASIER to make.<br>
<br>
We have designed, built, and run Nuclear Lightbulbs in the 70's.  I think we can make them work with todays technology, and I don't even think it would be that hard.  <br>
<br>
<br>
If you think otherwise, make your point to me.  But remember the stunning speed with which tech is moving these days.  All of the drawbacks which stumped us 30 years ago are quite solvable today.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  I am simply echoing (and concurring with) the policy of NASA ~AND~ the policy of the United Nations, not to use such a vehicle within the atmosphere.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
BAH.  I refuse to let a bunch of fat, tired, cover-your-ass, scared-for-their-jobs beaurocrats rule my thinking.  Hell, Columbus had to BEG for the money to make his little trip.  Short-sighted fools in government have been a problem for centuries.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
