AAAARGHH!!!  <br>
<br>
As I said before, I am not advocating a plain old gas core NTR.  I am advocating a Nuclear Lightbulb design.  <br>
<br>
THE FUEL IS ENCAPSULATED.  Honest.<br>
<br>
Am I writing my ideas poorly or something?  How do I make this clear to you guys?<br>
<br>
MY DESIGN HAS ZERO RADIOACTIVE EMISSIONS IN THE ATMOSPHERE.   <br>
<br>
The only way it CAN release rads in the biophere is if something goes VERY VERY wrong, and even then, the amount released in a worst case scenario is much less than what we have already released and dealt with successfully multiple times in the past due to the choice of launch site.<br>
<br>
This design is a fully reusable, single stage to orbit, heavy lift booster which has a cargo capacity of 1000 tons per flight.<br>
<br>
ONE THOUSAND TONS.  And it can fly BACK with that much cargo, something no other design I have ever heard of can do.  This is a system which could easily drive a needed paradigm shift in the way we think about space access.<br>
<br>
It is not wishful thinking or blue-sky science fiction ideas.  It would not be any harder to implement than Zaphod's beloved Orions.  (Care to get detailed on pusher plate design?  It AIN'T trivial.  Consider the issue of expanding circular shock waves in the plate generated as the spherical blast front impacts a flat plate.  Spalling at the edges is going to be TOUGH to control.  Using a non-flat pusher makes it difficult to use different sized bombs.  To solve this issue requires you use more than one pusher plate with holes in them to entrap and slow the shock wave as it comes in.)<br>
<br>
Please go back and re-read the information I have presented again.  Truly, this is not something I am just winging about as a &quot;what if&quot; scenario, I really am beginning to think this is a feasible approach.<br>
<br>
Not to imply yales may not poke a hole in it eventually, but it looks good so far.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
