 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 207<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/15/02 5:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: a ntr booster</span><hr size=1> One things I haven't seen in these designs, which I think you're missing out on, is multi-mode operation.<br>
Consider things like O2 afterburners and tripropellant operation. See what the increased thrust of afterburners or adding CH4 for the first few minutes does to your fuel use. (O2 is heavier, but more dense. Even if the fuel mass goes up, the overall mass may drop because of the decreased tankage &amp; airframe.)<br>
<br>
 I'm holding still on this for now. What's the consensus on the level of radiological danger in an accident?<br>
 You can never factor everything in. If there's an accident, what assurance do you offer to safety of containment? What about accidents in all flight regimes?<br>
 Sure, it sounds safe, but if Murphy smacks you down, it's pretty horrendous for one of these things. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/umauk2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/15/02 11:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: a ntr booster</span><hr size=1> Oooh!  More interest.  Me like! <br>
<br>
Tim1965:  The operating temperatures are not really<br>
the problem.  The issue arises from the transmissivity<br>
properties of the lightbulb material.  <br>
<br>
I have already posited some fairly extreme cooling measures (high volume cold hydrogen liquid gas flowing through a three layer lightbulb) which should be more than adequate to deal with the simple thermal loads due to conduction of heat from the working fluids, especially if hydrogen gas is allowed the &quot;bleed through&quot; the layers of the lightbulb using micropores.  <br>
<br>
No, the issue arises because a gas core NTR uses radiative cooling as both the way of cooling the core and as the method of heating the reaction gas.  If the material used in the lightbulb (likely silica, but possibly something else) is perfectly transparent to the full spectum of the radiative energy, then the loads on the lightbulb remain quite small.  <br>
<br>
If the lightbulb is &quot;opaque&quot; to say ten percent of the radiative energy, then the amount of energy the bulb has to dissipate skyrockets.  Yales has used a figure of 3 gigawatts per engine, and that is a fair number, I feel.<br>
<br>
(Note, by radiative energy I mean photons, and the information I am able to get indicates they are photons of about 5 electron volts.  Or, they are radiated by a material at a temperature around 55,000 Kelvin.)<br>
<br>
So, I think the more elegant solution is to simply work up lightbulb materials that meet the required &quot;transparency&quot; issues.   I did a little more poking around and discovered that 5ev photons are almost EXACTLY the same energy as are required for deep ultraviolet lithography techniques, and HUGE amounts of work is being done on transparency in those wavelengths.  For example, see <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://wwwsoc.nii.ac.jp/crsj/journal02/abstract-44-3.html"> this page </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and ctrl-f on ultraviolet to find a brief citation.  So, again, I will express confience that the transparency issue can be resolved.    <br>
<br>
Failing that,  we have to work out a way to cool the lightbulb.  Assuming the lightbulb is 1 meter in diameter by 3 meters long, the surface area is approximately ten square meters.  So, we need to engineer a solution to cool 300 megawatts per square meter.  (YIKES!)  <br>
<br>
I have read of NTR design projects working to reach a target of 100 megawatts per square meter of cooling, so it may not be impossible.  I suspect the actual solution will be a combination of both approaches.<br>
<br>
<br>
Neutron embrittlement is a much meaner problem.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I have not read anything of the detailed physics of the reaction in a gas cored reactor, but not for lack of trying to find it.  I have a suspicion that the majority of the neutrons from the core are moderated/absorbed in the gaseous outer fringes of the UF6 cloud, but I could be wrong.<br>
<br>
The simple way to handle neutron embrittlement in the lightbulb is to simply replace it after a period of time, say three launches.  Three launches should be less than an hour total exposure time, I can't imagine there being enough neutron damage to the bulb to cause problems in that timeframe.  It should be no issue to simply swap out the lightbulb for a fresh one, after all, it is basically a fancy piece of glass.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
See, not all of my solutions are &quot;tightly engineered&quot; sometimes they just consist of &quot;get a new one.&quot;  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
John Fraz: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  One things I haven't seen in these designs, which I think you're missing out on, is multi-mode operation. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yeah, the Isp of the nuclear rocket is so high I did not want to introduce the additional complexity of multimodal operations.  Since the exhaust consists of mainly monatomic hydrogen, there is plenty of energy to be scavenged simply by allowing it to recombine and then combusting it with air.  I considered shaping the entire aft end of the rocket as a &quot;plug nozzle&quot; to capture this energy, but I decided the problem of keeping that much area cool was just not worth it....<br>
<br>
Now, one issue that DID strike my fancy would be to use a venturi effect to draw ambient air into the expansion nozzle for the first 20 seconds of flight or so.  The reason is to combat the loss of Isp due to sea level external air pressure.  We would drop the Isp even further by doing this, but since the extra reaction mass increases thrust and is NOT being accelerated I could see this option being of use. <br>
<br>
After the first 20 seconds, air pressure has dropped enough that the engines will be producing near vacuum thrust and Isp figures, so the air scoops could be shut down.  This would be more complexity, but not nearly as much as a true bi or tri modal design.  Remember my design criteria: Big but Relaxed.  Following the KISS principal is high on my list.<br>
<br>
As for the radiological risks, I have stated before that I think they are easily mitigated by launching from Baker Island out in the middle of the Pacific.  The Pacific Ocean is HUGE.  Even in the event of a total loss of the vehicle and total failure of all scram modes and containment devices, the radiation release is far below what we have released there in the past and successfully mitigated.  So, I feel it is plenty safe enough.<br>
<br>
As for the assurances of safety, as I stated before, the design is MASSIVELY overbuilt, and then has MASSIVE redundancy, using different systems to reach the same ends.  There comes a point when you are obsessively trying to reach that ninth &quot;9&quot; when it simply is not worth it.<br>
<br>
As for flight regimes, boost phase is the riskiest in my mind, followed by the descent phase.  I have explained at great length the safety factors built into the boost phase above.<br>
<br>
Descent phase is less risky because the ship uses light aerobraking to do much of the work, so the engines are VERY lightly loaded on the way down.  It would land on its tender ship as I described above (liberally protected by water sprays) or on Baker Island on a flooded pad.  Note, this is a powered fly-down, there is no chance of the ship veering off course and landing on Chicago or something. <br>
<br>
The worst point for a catastrophic failure of all confinement would be either right before or after it leaves orbit.  However, the seven fuel stores would be designed to survive any level of re-entry stress (as I detailed above) and there are two different mechanisms for getting the fuel into the fuel storage.  (Simple vacuum and a set of redundant pumps.)<br>
<br>
<br>
Oh, yales is not going to ask me about the fuel cycle, so I'll just volunteer it now:<br>
<br>
At every launch, the fuel storage systems are charged shourtly before launch with pressurized uranium hexaflouride.  This is then chilled until it solidifies, which drops the pressure in the system close to zero.  When it is time to launch, a portion of the fuel system is heated with resistance wires to allow the UF6 in that portion of the system to to sublime back to gas.  The rest remains as a solid. The amount which is gaseous is pumped slowly into the lightbulb until it lights up, while the rest stays in the storage system of thick walled aluminum boron tubing.<br>
<br>
Once the craft has reached orbit, the now very hotly radioactive UF6 gas from the lightbulb is pumped into a different section of the storage system.  <br>
<br>
When the ship is launched, the orbit it is destined for is usually circular, which requires a &quot;circularizationn burn.&quot;  With this ship, since it has so much power to burn, it is deliberately launched into a higher orbit than is needed, so that the circularization burn is actually removing some delta v again.<br>
<br>
Why in the world do that?  Well, during the circularization burn, the ship is turned so that the main engines are pointing in the direction of travel.  When the burn is performed, the exhaust gases leave earth's orbit with a total combined speed of around 35 to 40 kilometers per second.  <br>
<br>
This is enough speed to ensure that the gas leaves the Earth essentially forever.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
The storage systems that hold the spent fuel from the boost phase are plumbed to the exhaust nozzle of the engine used for the circularization burn!  So, as the ship achieves orbital insertion, it also LITERALLY shoots  85 percent of the waste it generated on the trip up into space!  (And yes, there are both active and passive safterties on that valving system so accidental releases are VERY difficult.<br>
<br>
So, in a way, this ship could be seen as REMOVING radiocative waste from the environment permanently!  Heck, all the anti-nuclear advocates should be supporting this design, as it can literally shoot radioactive waste into the Sun!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
As for other flight regimes:  The system is pretty fanatical about being simple.  There is no hydraulic system, all flight surfaces and other controls use electric servos.  The reaction control system, also known as the attitude thrusters, are NOT hydrazine, they are cold gas hydrogen jets, powered by bleedoff from the main hydrogen tank.  Heck, if all seven engines die, the booster can achieve almost 1 km/sec of delta V just from venting it's propellant tank!  This is a backup system to deorbit the machine if need be.<br>
<br>
There are very few &quot;fancy flier&quot; flight modes needed.  For example, the Space Shuttle has the &quot;Return to Pad&quot; flight regime.  This booster does not need this since it has SO much redundancy and is SO overbuilt it can fly to orbit on one engine if need be, after the first 60 seconds of flight has passed.  Heck, it can get off the launch pad with only 5!<br>
<br>
As for the &quot;horrendous&quot; point:  Any accident is horrendous, so yes I want it to be safe.  It is nigh impossible the achieve the type of world-ending catastrophe the Anti's rail on about with this machine.<br>
<br>
As I have said before, the risk is small, even total failure is manageable, and it is WORTH it.   This design could place more payload into orbit in TWO FLIGHTS than the Space Shuttle FLEET has placed into orbit <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.hq.nasa.gov/office/pao/facts/HTML/FS-005-HQ.html"> in its entire flight history. </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Impressive, huh.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
